Yeah, I tried to keep the same API as `set_hook`. Looking at the usages of `set_hook` in the compiler, I only see two kinds of calls:

* `set_hook(prev)`, where `prev` is the return of a previous call to `take_hook`
* `set_hook(Box::new(|info| { ... }))`, with custom code inside the closure

So I guess we can try to remove the explicit `Box` from `update_hook`.

As I mentioned in another comment it would be interesting to see if something like this is possible:

```rust
panic::update_hook(|prev, info| {
    println!("panic handler A");
    prev(info);
});
```

Which is nice because it removes one level of nested closures, and it would also handle the `box`ing internally.

> As I mentioned in another comment it would be interesting to see if something like this is possible:

Do you mean something like this?

```rust
#[unstable(feature = "panic_update_hook", issue = "92649")]
pub fn update_hook<F>(hook_fn: F)
where
    F: Fn(
        &(dyn Fn(&PanicInfo<'_>) + 'static + Sync + Send), &PanicInfo<'_>,
    ) + Send + Sync + 'static,
{
    if thread::panicking() {
        panic!("cannot modify the panic hook from a panicking thread");
    }

    unsafe {
        let guard = HOOK_LOCK.write();
        let old_hook = HOOK;
        HOOK = Hook::Default;

        let hook_for_fn = match old_hook {
            Hook::Default => Box::new(default_hook),
            Hook::Custom(ptr) => Box::from_raw(ptr),
        };

        HOOK = Hook::custom(move |info| hook_fn(&hook_for_fn, info));
        drop(guard);
    }
}

impl Hook {
    fn custom(f: impl Fn(&PanicInfo<'_>) + 'static + Sync + Send) -> Self {
        Self::Custom(Box::into_raw(Box::new(f)))
    }
}
```

I ran into some lifetime issues too when trying this that I'm assuming are the same ones you ran into:

```
error[E0308]: mismatched types
   --> library/std/src/panicking.rs:228:43
    |
228 |         HOOK = Hook::Custom(Box::into_raw(hook));
    |                                           ^^^^ one type is more general than the other
    |
    = note: expected type `for<'r, 's> Fn<(&'r PanicInfo<'s>,)>`
               found type `Fn<(&PanicInfo<'_>,)>`
```

Which ended up being an issue with how `for<...>` is uninferrable, but adding a new constructor lets you hint to the compiler the correct bounds. I don't entirely understand how introducing the constructor is avoiding inference for the closure so I don't think I can sufficiently explain how this fixes things. I had to have a friend from the compiler team help me figure it out, lol...

Edit: I asked a bunch of questions and am going to attempt to re-explain this. Turns out closures aren't subject to the same inference rules as the rest of the language because "higher-rank inference is undecidable, or so the nerds tell me". If the hook closure is assigned to a variable it goes through inference and fails to infer the `for` bound correctly, but if its used directly as the argument in a function the compiler never needs inference, because it already knows the expected type when figuring out the closures type and so it's able to get it right.

`PhantomData<T>` has e.g. [a `T: Send` bound/condition for `PhantomData<T>: Send`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/marker/struct.PhantomData.html#synthetic-implementations), while `fn() -> T` is unconditionally `Send` (and similarly for all the other auto-traits).

Auto-traits work by considering the types of the fields, hence `BuildHasherDefault<H>: Send` if and only if all it's field types are `Send`; i.e.  `BuildHasherDefault<H>: Send` used to require `PhantomData<H>: Send`, which in turn requires `H: Send`, while after this PR, it will require  `PhantomData<fn() -> H>: Send`, which in turn requires `fn() -> H: Send`, which is true unconditionally:
````rs
fn function_requiring_send<T: Send>() {}

fn demonstration<H /* not necessarily `Send */>() {
    function_requiring_send::<fn() -> H>(); // works!
}
````

