It would be a lot of hard work to encode the structure of Rust paths using Itanium mangling, and that might not be exactly a successful endeavour, so I think we should avoid doing so (unless it is for some reason important?). Instead I would suggest using opaque type identifiers for nominal types.

To sketch a potential implementation:

```rust
fn encode_def_path<'tcx>(
    tcx: TyCtxt<'tcx>,
    name: &str,
    def_id: DefId,
    substs: &'tcx [GenericArg<'tcx>],
) -> String {
    let mut hasher = StableHasher::new();
    let hcx = &mut tcx.create_stable_hashing_context();
    tcx.def_path_hash(def_id).hash_stable(hcx, &mut hasher);
    substs.hash_stable(hcx, &mut hasher);
    let s = format!("{name}{:x}", hasher.finish::<u64>());
    format!("u{}{}", s.len(), s)
}
```

I would use this kind of implementation for Adt, Foreign, FnDef, Closure, Generator, (take a look at v0 / legacy mangling to see if there is anything more that would fall into this case).

