LLVM CFI (i.e., forward-edge control flow protection) usually[^1] aggregates function pointers in groups identified by their return and parameter types, and before indirect calls, test whether the destination pointer is associated with a type identifier (i.e., test type membership) of all possible destinations for that indirect call. For instance:

```rust
fn A(i32) {};
fn B(i32) {};
fn C(i32) {};
```
A type test membership at an indirect call site that calls a function that returns unit type (or void) and receives a single i32 parameter should pass for A, B, and C.

[^1]: This is the amount of information that its currently only existing implementation uses, which is Clang's implementation (where LLVM CFI was initially implemented).

